% ====================================================================
% test_gc_local_dict_global_ref.trx -- Phases A + B regression
% ====================================================================
% Phase 10 GC walks the global VM region only.  Pre-Phases-A/B,
% gc_mark_object silent-skipped any Object whose offset pointed below
% m_vm_global.  That left a coverage gap: LOCAL Dict / Set / Tagged /
% Array values holding global refs would have those globals reclaimed
% mid-iteration once the local container's only outer reference was a
% global container slot or a Trix root that gc_mark_object passed
% through.
%
% Phases A + B (plan_gc_walks_local_containers.md) plug the gap:
%   * Phase A: when gc_mark_object's range check fires and the Object is
%     Dict/Set, dispatch to Dict::gc_walk_contents on the local
%     payload.
%   * Phase B: extend the dispatch to local Tagged (2 Objects at
%     fixed offsets) and local Array (Object[arrays_length()]).
% An auxiliary visited-offset set (m_gc_local_visited, capacity 1024)
% breaks cycles across all four kinds -- local blocks have no
% GvmBlock header so the per-block m_mark_gen short-circuit doesn't
% apply.  Phase C (local Packed) has its own regression file:
% test_gc_local_packed_global_ref.trx.
%
% This test exercises the paths end-to-end:
%   * Allocate global Arrays (via `${ ... }`).
%   * Store each Array into a LOCAL container (Dict, Tagged, or
%     plain Array; no `${...}` wrap on the container itself).
%   * Wire the local container up through userdict (global) so it's
%     reachable from a Trix root.
%   * Drop every other reference to the global Array.
%   * GC.
%   * Force the freed memory to be reissued so a stale offset reads
%     scratch values, not coincidentally-intact bytes.
%   * Verify the global Array's payload is still intact (length,
%     element values).  Without Phase A/B, GC reclaims the Array
%     and the slot reads return scratch values -- assertions fire.
% ====================================================================

% rt-ok counts failures in a restore-immune slot -- string byte writes
% are unjournaled, so the count survives assertions made inside save
% scopes, and the 1-byte string lives in LOCAL VM, invisible to the
% global-heap/gc-counter probes some files assert on.  The file THROWS
% at EOF: test_all counts a file as failed only when its run throws,
% so print-only failures would slip the suite verdict.
/rt-fails 1 string def
rt-fails 0 16#0#b put
/rt-ok { exch { = } { (FAILED: ) print = rt-fails 0  rt-fails 0 get /integer-type cast 1 add dup 255 gt { pop 255 } if /byte-type cast  put } if-else } def

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% After GC, forcibly re-use the freed memory.  Phase 10 GC marks
% blocks free in the allocator but doesn't zero their storage; so a
% dangling Object that reads its old slot can spuriously look
% intact until the storage is reused.  Allocating a stream of
% same-size global Arrays after each GC pass guarantees the freed
% block gets re-issued -- if the retained Array's slots still read
% their original values after that, the GC was actually doing its
% job (i.e., Phase A walked the local container and kept the
% Array alive).
% --------------------------------------------------------------------
/force-reuse {
    |length|#1
    0 1 9 {
        /i exch def
        ${ length array } /scratch exch def
        0 1 length 1 sub {
            /j exch def
            scratch j j 999 add put-persist
        } for
        /scratch null def
    } for
} def

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% SECTION 1: global Array reachable only through local Dict via userdict
% --------------------------------------------------------------------

/runs0 //:status:gc-runs def

% Build a 50-element global Array; fill with 0..49.
${ 50 array } /retain-payload exch def
0 1 49 {
    /i exch def
    retain-payload i i put-persist
} for

% Build a local Dict (no ${...} wrap; vm_alloc, sub-m_vm_global) and
% stash the global Array in it.  /local-holder lives in userdict
% (global), so the chain is: userdict -> local-holder (LOCAL) ->
% retain-payload (GLOBAL).
4 dict /local-holder exch def
local-holder /payload retain-payload put-persist

% Drop the direct top-level handle so the LOCAL dict is the only
% remaining path to the global Array.
/retain-payload null def

% Real GC.  Should NOT reclaim the global Array's payload (reachable
% through the local Dict).  Phase A's local-Dict walk dispatches
% Dict::gc_walk_contents on the local-holder offset, which calls
% gc_mark_object on /payload's value -- the global Array -- and marks it
% live.  Without Phase A, gc_mark_object range-skips the local-holder
% Dict, the Array goes unmarked, and the sweep frees its block.
/reclaimed1 vm-global-gc def

% Force any freed 50-element-Array storage to be reissued so a
% dangling reference manifests as garbage instead of stale-but-
% intact-by-coincidence values.
50 force-reuse

% Pull the Array back out and verify length + sampled elements.
% Phase A's dispatch made the local-holder Dict's contents reachable
% to gc_mark_object; without it, the Array's block was reclaimed and
% then overwritten by the force-reuse pass -- the slot reads would
% return scratch's filled-in `j 999 add` values (or null after
% scratch's own /scratch null def + the next sweep).
local-holder /payload get /payload exch def
payload length 50 eq                          (1: payload length intact post-GC) rt-ok
payload 0  get 0  eq                          (1: payload[0] intact) rt-ok
payload 25 get 25 eq                          (1: payload[25] intact) rt-ok
payload 49 get 49 eq                          (1: payload[49] intact) rt-ok

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% SECTION 2: nested local Dicts forming a chain to the global ref
% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% Two nested local Dicts; the inner one holds the global ref.  The
% outer one references the inner.  Both are local; outer is rooted
% in userdict.  Validates that gc_mark_object's local-Dict walk
% recurses through nested local Dicts (the visited set prevents
% double-walks but doesn't block the descent).

${ 30 array } /inner-payload exch def
0 1 29 { /i exch def inner-payload i i 100 add put-persist } for

4 dict /inner-d exch def
inner-d /payload inner-payload put-persist

4 dict /outer-d exch def
outer-d /child inner-d put-persist

/inner-payload null def
/inner-d        null def

vm-global-gc /reclaimed2 exch def
30 force-reuse

% outer-d is in userdict (global).  Reach the global Array through
% outer -> child (LOCAL Dict) -> /payload.
outer-d /child get /payload get /payload exch def
payload length 30 eq                          (2: nested-walked Array length intact) rt-ok
payload 0  get 100 eq                         (2: nested payload[0] intact) rt-ok
payload 15 get 115 eq                         (2: nested payload[15] intact) rt-ok
payload 29 get 129 eq                         (2: nested payload[29] intact) rt-ok

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% SECTION 3: cycle between two local Dicts holding a global ref
% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% Two local Dicts pointing at each other PLUS one of them holding a
% global ref.  Tests the visited-set cycle break: without it,
% gc_mark_object would recurse infinitely through the local-Dict A ->
% local-Dict B -> local-Dict A -> ... chain.

${ 16 array } /cycle-payload exch def
0 1 15 { /i exch def cycle-payload i i 200 add put-persist } for

4 dict /cycle-a exch def
4 dict /cycle-b exch def
cycle-a /peer cycle-b put-persist
cycle-b /peer cycle-a put-persist
cycle-a /payload cycle-payload put-persist

/cycle-payload null def
/cycle-b        null def

% Run GC.  If the visited set isn't doing its job, this hangs or
% overflows.  If Phase A isn't walking the local cycle, the global
% Array is reclaimed and the post-GC access trips an error.
vm-global-gc /reclaimed3 exch def
16 force-reuse

% Reach the global Array through the cycle: cycle-a -> /peer
% (cycle-b) -> /peer (cycle-a) -> /payload.
cycle-a /peer get /peer get /payload get /payload exch def
payload length 16 eq                          (3: cyclic-walked Array length intact) rt-ok
payload 0  get 200 eq                         (3: cyclic payload[0] intact) rt-ok
payload 8  get 208 eq                         (3: cyclic payload[8] intact) rt-ok
payload 15 get 215 eq                         (3: cyclic payload[15] intact) rt-ok

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% SECTION 4: local Tagged value holding a global Array (Phase B)
% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% A Tagged value created without `${...}` lands in local VM (its
% 2-Object payload is vm_alloc'd).  When that Tagged carries a
% global ref as its value field and is rooted via userdict, GC must
% walk the Tagged's payload to keep the global alive.  This is the
% mini-scheme primitives-dict shape: each /primitive-tagged value
% wraps a global proc body.

${ 24 array } /tagged-payload exch def
0 1 23 { /i exch def tagged-payload i i 300 add put-persist } for

% `payload /local-bag tag` -- creates a 2-Object Tagged
% [/local-bag, payload].  Without ${...} prefix, lands in local VM.
tagged-payload /local-bag tag /local-tag exch def
/tagged-payload null def

vm-global-gc /reclaimed4 exch def
24 force-reuse

local-tag tag-value /payload exch def
payload length 24 eq                          (4: tagged-walked Array length intact) rt-ok
payload 0  get 300 eq                         (4: tagged payload[0] intact) rt-ok
payload 12 get 312 eq                         (4: tagged payload[12] intact) rt-ok
payload 23 get 323 eq                         (4: tagged payload[23] intact) rt-ok

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% SECTION 5: local Array containing a global Array (Phase B)
% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% A local Array (no `${...}`) holding a global Array as element 0.
% Same shape as Section 4 but using a plain Array as the local
% container.

${ 18 array } /inner-array exch def
0 1 17 { /i exch def inner-array i i 400 add put-persist } for

% `1 array` returns a local 1-element Array; put-persist inner-array
% into slot 0.
1 array /local-arr exch def
local-arr 0 inner-array put-persist
/inner-array null def

vm-global-gc /reclaimed5 exch def
18 force-reuse

local-arr 0 get /payload exch def
payload length 18 eq                          (5: array-walked Array length intact) rt-ok
payload 0  get 400 eq                         (5: array payload[0] intact) rt-ok
payload 9  get 409 eq                         (5: array payload[9] intact) rt-ok
payload 17 get 417 eq                         (5: array payload[17] intact) rt-ok

% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% SECTION 6: probe sees retained globals as live
% --------------------------------------------------------------------
% After all the dust settles, the probe should see at least the
% five retained Array payloads as live.

vm-global-gc-probe /probe-final exch def
probe-final /live get 5 ge                    (6: probe sees >= 5 live retained) rt-ok

rt-fails 0 get /integer-type cast 0 gt { /rt-assertions-failed throw } if
(test_gc_local_dict_global_ref: ALL TESTS PASSED) =
(__test_ok__) =
